threat_severity.level_description: Severity HIGH because it was considered ransomware. Other contributing factors were that it has known exploits and it could not be run in sandboxes.

attributes.magic: ELF 32-bit LSB executable, Intel 80386, version 1 (SYSV), statically linked, for GNU/Linux 2.6.9, not stripped

crowdsourced_ai_results.analysis: This ELF binary is a Linux ransomware sample designed to daemonize, traverse the filesystem, and encrypt user data. Upon execution, it forks into the background, creates a new session, and begins a 'heartbeat' loop that recursively searches for files in sensitive directories including /home, /root, /opt, and Oracle-style database paths (/u01, /u02, /u03, /u04). It utilizes hardcoded RC4 routines for file encryption and drops a ransom note named 'README_C_I_0P.TXT' in processed directories. The note includes contact emails (unlock@support-mult.com, unlock@rsv-box.com) and a Tor-based (.onion) payment/chat portal. Hardcoded cryptographic keys and standard ransomware behavior definitively classify this as malicious.
